Experiment I 
Objective: Demonstrate version control using Git. 
Required Software / Tools: GIT, Python, VSCode 
Procedure: 
1. Set up a Working directory or folder as below: 
Open Visual Studio > Menu options > File > Open Folder > Right click > create New 
Folder with name Exp1. 
2. Now open terminal from visual studio (Visual Studio > Menu options > Terminal > 
New Terminal) 
3. From the terminal run below commands to initialize git in the Exp1 folder.  
git init 
git status 
4. Create a file (on VSCode left pane click + New file) and name it greet.py. On right pane 
write a basic Python program as below: 
# Basic Python Program - Version 1 
print("Hello, World!") 
5. Save the file and move to git Stage and commit the file using below commands: 
git add greet.py 
git commit -m "Initial commit: add greet.py" 
NOTE: check git status before each and after command execution. 
6. Edit the file as below to make a change to the program and save the file.  
# Basic Python Program - Version 2 
print("Hello, Git versioning!") 
7. Add the updated file to git Stage and commit the change 
git add greet.py 
git commit -m "Updated greet.py version2" 
NOTE: check git status before each and after command execution. 
8. At this moment, we have performed two commits. Check the commit history using 
command: git log  
9. Revert to a previous version using commit id from git log and check the file content on 
above screen automatically reverts to version based on the commit id. 
git checkout <commit_id> greet.py 
NOTE: <commit_id> should be updated according to which version you want to restore 
from git log command. 
eg: git checkout be1ecb4be35c76f92a18887dcab39f3bbea63afb greet.py 
